post_text: Distance Learning parents: We will be making a few changes to our Google Meets settings. Starting tomorrow, your child will not be able to join a Google Meets session before the teacher does. If you try to do so, you may receive a “You’re not allowed to create Meets” error. The reason for this change is we have had kids beat the teacher into the meeting, and this takes away the moderator control of the meet from the teacher. By making sure the teacher gets in first, this will allow the teacher to control the Meet much better and make the experience better for everyone. This change will happen starting tomorrow at 8:00AM. Please let us know if there are any questions or issues, and thank you for your understanding and supporting distance learning!

By making sure the teacher gets in first, this will allow the teacher to control the Meet much better and make the experience better for everyone. This change will happen starting tomorrow at 8:00AM. Whirlwinds
August 24, 2020

Dear Parents,

FCHS and FCJH is committed to improving our instructional practices, using student performance data in making instructional decisions and utilizing technology to improve instruction. We use time on most Tuesday mornings to focus on increasing student success. We call this time PLC and it stands for Professional Learning Communities.

Our PLC time for teacher growth is from 7:40am to 8:30am. First period on PLC days begins at 8:40am. We have set the following dates for our first six weeks PLC meetings.
Tuesday, August 25
Tuesday, September 1
Tuesday, September 15
Tuesday, September 22
Tuesday, September 29

If you have questions about PLC please contact the school at 806-983-4970.

Go Winds!

Wayne Morren

post_text:
Guidelines for Whirlwinds Scrimmage on 8/20/2020

1. UIL rules state that schools are limited to a maximum of 50% occupancy of a stadium; therefore, we will only allow 750 spectators at the scrimmage tomorrow evening.

2. Social distancing (6 feet) is required between groups that are not in the same household.

3. Masks or face coverings (over nose and mouth) will be required in the stadium for all spectators. Exceptions to the wearing of face coverings or face shields are as follows:
a. Any person with a medical condition or disability that prevents wearing of a face covering
b. While a person is consuming food or drink
c. When a congregating group of persons in the same household maintains at least 6 feet of social distancing

4. Hand sanitizing stations will be provided throughout the stadium and at all entrances.

5. Seating, handrails, and other common surfaces will be cleaned and disinfected prior to each game.

6. Restrooms will be cleaned and disinfected several times throughout the evening.

7. There is no entry fee for scrimmages.

post_text:
Attention Duncan Parents,

Thank you for your patience and grace as we work to make sure all children are dismissed in a safe and orderly fashion.

To help the flow of afternoon dismissal traffic, starting today, August, 18th, we will dismiss pre-k and kindergarten students beginning at 3:30. All parents of pre-k and kindergarten students will pull through the traffic line on the south side of the building to pick your child up. If you have other children in 1st-5th grades, we kindly ask that you circle back through the dismissal line at 3:45 to pick them up.

Students in 1st-5th grade will dismiss at 3:45. Parents, please pull through the traffic line on the south side of the building beginning at 3:45 to pick your child up.

If you arrive early during the pre-k and kindergarten dismissal, and have children in 1st-5th grades, we will kindly ask that you circle back around at 3:45 to prevent traffic from backing up.

If your child rides a bus, they will run at 3:45 as normal.

We appreciate your support!

post_text:
Mandatory Remote Learning for Jr High /High School

We want to ensure that all students are prepared for learning while at home. The state has provided additional expectations for student learning from home this fall. We need everyone to be aware of the changes and how we are going to support them. We will host a mandatory meeting for virtual learners and their parents on Monday, August 17. Our Junior High meeting will begin at 5:00pm. The High School meeting will begin at 6:00pm. The meetings will be held in the school cafeteria. Students will be issued their laptops and we will discuss the expectations for student growth. During this meeting, all parents and children must wear a face covering and enter the building using the main entrance located on the south side of the building. Please arrive on time.

Floydada ISD is transitioning to a new telephone system. We will soon have more advanced features like district-wide transfer and voicemail! Unfortunately, due to this change the old high school building is now unable to take phone calls. We are working to get the new phones up at the new school as soon as possible. In the meantime, please email our counselors with any needs.You can find a full staff e-mail listing here: https://www.floydadaisd.esc17.net/o/district/staff

If you are unable to email us for any reason, please call our Elementary campus and our staff there can relay the message along.

We apologize for this inconvenience. We'll post an update when our new campus is connected. Thank you for your patience as we transition to our new facility!

post_text:
Official News Release:

Erin Trevino, sophomore at Floydada High School, was recently named to the 1st Team Academic All-State Team in Softball by the Texas High School Coaches Association and the Texas Army National Guard. Recipients of this honor excel in the following categories: GPA, class rank, and ACT/SAT score. Erin excelled as a pitcher and infielder for the Lady Winds during the 2019-2020 season. She had 70 strikeouts and hit .360 in a COVID-19 shortened season. We commend Erin for her commitment and dedication to perform with high standards of excellence on the field as well as in the classroom.

*** Attention Mrs. Snowden's 2019-20 6th grade students. ***

Mrs. Snowden received a grant with the Keep Kids Learning program through DonorsChoose and was able to purchase items for her students to use this summer. The care packages will be distributed on Thursday, June 4th, and Friday, June 5th from 4-6 pm at the drive-through in the back parking lot of the First Baptist Church. Attention Kindergarten Parents/Guardians:



Monday, May 18th from 9:00-10:30 is iPad drop off for Kindergarten students. If you would like to have your child’s photo taken in a cap and gown, please complete the Google form link. We will be set up by the marquee sign at AB Duncan. Keep in mind that we will abide by social distancing guidelines, so you and your child will need to remain in your vehicle until it is your turn for a picture. In order to avoid a long wait time, please complete the needed information in the Google form and choose an available time slot. When the photos are complete we will send you a JPEG image for you to print and share at your convenience.



We look forward to making a memorable moment with your child!

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLScfoeUVqBqavxhCGW4kaTYjZ62yQOqc43XqtEdx1DbceyIOzg/viewform

It has been brought to our attention that we are having issues with students submitting an assignment online and the assignment is somehow lost. Please know that we understand the frustration. This is new to all of us. We are looking into it since the issue seems to be beyond the student, teacher, or district's control. We will try to resolve the issue quickly, but in the meantime, we will ask that our teachers be understanding of possible technical issues and not penalize students for something that is beyond their control. If this has happened to your child, please contact an administrator. The contact information is as follows:
Duncan: Wayne Morren wmorren@floydadaisd.esc17.net or Monica Smith msmith@floydadaisd.esc17.net

FJH/FHS: Wayne Morren or Dara Ware dware@floydadaisd.esc17.net

5th Graders Seek Donations to Honor Seniors.

5th graders began a service project before Spring Break to raise money to give 2 scholarships to Floydada High School Seniors. They had a Snack Shack to sell Candy but with the Coronovirus Pandemic, we were not able to raise enough money . We are accepting donations to hopefully have enough to honor 2 of our Floydada Seniors. If you would like to donate, contact Laura Nutt or Jan Beedy. You can send us a private message on Facebook and we will make arrangements to get your donation. Thank you so much!

Coughing & sneezing can send tiny infected droplets into the air which can be inhaled by anyone within 6 feet of us. Always cough or sneeze into a tissue or your elbow and immediately wash your hands to lessen the risk of spreading the virus. Be smart. Stay well! #StayHomeTexas

Toser y estornudar puede llevar gotas infectadas al aire, que pueden ser inhaladas por personas que estén a 6 pies de ti. Siempre tosa o estornude en pañuelos desechables o en el codo y lávese las manos para disminuir la propagación del virus. ¡Mantente sano! #StayHomeTexas

• Evite salir en público
• Cuando esté en público, mantenga una distancia de seis pies entre usted y los demás.
• Seguir las recomendaciones de los funcionarios locales y estatales.
Obtenga más información en https://texas.gov/covid19

• When in public, keep six feet of distance between you and others
• Follow guidance provided by local and state officials.

post_text:
Parents and Guardians,

Thank you to those who have completed the Information for Remote Learning Survey. If you have not already done so, please take the time to complete the information.

FISD is using Google Classroom as a means to provide instruction to your child during this time. Students in grades 5-12 have a gmail address provided by the school. However, students in PK-4th grade do not have gmail addresses. In order to accept the invite to Google Classroom, you must provide a gmail address. It is absolutely free to create an account. Just go to www.gmail.com.

Once you have completed the Information for Remote Learning Survey, your child’s teacher will send you an invite for Google Classroom. We will begin remote classes on Monday, March 30th.

https://docs.google.com/forms/d/e/1FAIpQLSe35A_eDP046sRobSj5M8NTEdy_5w6BN4ZOL78s9rFLIfxSpg/viewform?usp=sf_link

Thank you for partnering with FISD to ensure your child receives a quality learning experience during this unique time in education.

Go Whirlwinds!!

Parents and Guardians,

Floydada ISD is committed to ensuring your child receives a quality education under the conditions created by COVID-19. Our teachers are using Google Classroom as a means to communicate and help your student continue to learn. Your child’s teacher will send a link via the email you entered on the Remote Learning Survey. When you click on the link, you will be prompted to join their classroom. You will need a gmail email to access Google Classroom. Students in grades 5-12 have an account through the school. Parents who have children in PreK-4th grade will need to create an account. It is completely free to create an email account with gmail. Just go to www.gmail.com and create your account. We look forward to partnering with you in your child’s education!

AgTexas Farm Credit Services
February 10 at 2:48 PM ·

In small rural communities, like Floydada, students have the opportunity to be involved in many areas - scholastics, FFA, athletics and community service.

In reading Andrez application, he sees these as more than opportunities - "I make it a point to be involved and contribute to the success of our school in as many ways as I possibly can." He also says, "Volunteering is at the cornerstone of our FFA organization....I make sure to spend time to help younger students with their project."

Exactly the student we had in mind when we designed AgTexas Ag Youth of the Month.

#AgYouthStrong

post_text: 5thgrade is doing an experiment on decomposition. In November we put a pumpkin in an air-tight container and have been watching the changes that are taking place. The class named the pumpkin “Alexander” and they are recording changes in their science journals. Today they noticed that there is more mold and juice in the container. We can’t wait to see what happens next!

Whirlwind Band
On Thursday, January 16, 2020 fifteen students auditioned at Abernathy High School for the All-Region Band. Jody Briones (flute), Kaylea Britt (clarinet), Noah Vega (trombone), and Devin Reyes (percussion) made the band, and Siobhan Garza (clarinet) and Thomas Longoria (tuba) were alternates. The competition from others in the region was strong - we are very proud of their hard work and good fortune. The students will attend the All-Region weekend in Lubbock on January 23-25. Gooooooo Whirlwinds!

January Student and Staff of the Month
The Floydada I.S.D. Board met on Thursday, January 16 and recognized the following students and staff for their efforts to make education the best it can be. Each month the staff selects students that exemplify education at its best and those students are recognized at the monthly school board meeting. January students and staff for A.B.Duncan student recognized were Kyan Radler and Madisyn Zepeda grade 2. The Floydada Junior High Students of the month were Reynatisha Sanchez and Aiden Trevino, grade 8. The Floydada High School students recognized were Kaleb Crone and Dylan Ramos, grade 11. The secondary support staff of the month was Leslie Flores. Congratulations to each of these students and employees and thank you for your hard work.

post_text:
Beverly Collins: FISD Board Trustee

FISD appreciates your dedication and tirelessly hours spent to our District's success!

Collins has served on the board for 5 years and represents Precinct 4. She graduated from Plainview High School. Beverly is the Director of Floyd County Daycare located in downtown Floydada. When she isn’t busy with school board responsibilities, Collins enjoys watching grandchildren's sports. Beverly has 4 adult children and 7 beautiful grandchildren. Her vision for FISD is every student is at their maximum potential since these students are our future. Beverly's focus is on student achievement and implanting policies that would ensure success in all our students.

post_text:
Brianne Glasscock: FISD Board Trustee

FISD appreciates your dedication and tirelessly hours spent to our District's success!

Glasscock is in her first year of serving on the board. She represents Precinct 1. Brianne graduated from Littlefield High School and is the Vice President and Compliance Officer at First National Bank. She is married to Tate and has 2 children, Trace and Tatum. Brianne loves to read, travel and watch her children play sports. Her vision for the district is we have a greater number of students graduating prepared for their future not just for college, but with skills for the real world and career readiness. Her favorite part of serving on the board is hopefully making a difference for future generations and helping make our district and community a success.

post_text:
Eric Smith: FISD Board Trustee

FISD appreciates your dedication and tirelessly hours spent to our District's success!

Smith has recently been elected to be part of the FISD school board. “It’s a pleasant honor to be working with extraordinary people who work to make a difference in campuses”, said Smith. Smith graduated from Floydada High School in 1994 and then he attended Texas Tech. He is now a farmer and rancher and when he is not working he enjoys spending time with his family, wife Leigh, a hair stylist in Floydada, and sons Ethan and Logan.

post_text:
Gracie Diaz: FISD Board Trustee

FISD appreciates your dedication and tirelessly hours spent to our District's success!

Diaz has served on the board for 5 years. She grew up in Floydada and graduated from Floydada High School. She attended South Plains College. She is a dental assistant at Cogdell Clinic for 13 years. Gracie is married to her high school sweetheart, Art Diaz, and has 1 son, Zeph. Her hobbies include taking pictures of newborns and toddlers. “My vision for out district is to make sure we provide high quality learning for all students that incorporates technology and promotes student success in college and/or careers.”, said Diaz. Her favorite part of serving on the board is watching students succeed and accomplish their goals.

post_text: On Saturday, December 14, 2019 three students travelled to Levelland, TX to compete in the High School All-Region Honor Band Auditions. All three deserve congratulations: Noah Vega was the only Freshman trombonist to audition out of the entire region; Devin Reyes was only four spots away from making the band and was one of only three freshmen percussionists in the entire region to audition; and Jacob Johnston placed 2nd on Contra Alto Clarinet, making the Honor Band and advancing to All-Area Auditions on January 11, 2020. Jacob will get to perform in one of the finest region ensembles in the state on January 24-25 under the direction of one of the most successful conductors in the country. This is truly a high honor. If you see any of these fine young gentlemen, please congratulate their hard work and great sacrifice – both were necessary to have done so well!

post_text: Mrs. Snowden’s Science classes explored the layers of the Earth this week. They created a mixture of corn starch and water to better understand the asthenosphere’s property of plasticity. They also made models of the Earth with boiled eggs. They cracked up the egg shells and then dyed the eggs to better understand how the crust is a solid but broken into plates. Ask your students what layers the egg white and yolk represent.

post_text: We appreciate everyone's support and concern today as we dealt with a threat made on social media. With the help of the local Police Department and Department of Public Safety, we were able to ensure our students and staff were safe at all times. We have not discovered the origin of the threat nor did we find any evidence that anyone was ever in any danger. We will continue to ensure the safety of our students and staff. Thanks for your patience and trust in our district.

post_text: FHS and FJHS is teaming up with Prosperity Bank and South Plains Food Bank in the “U Can Share Food Drive”. Meagan Brittan from South Plains Food Bank and Zach Cumming from Prosperity Bank gave a presentation on the importance of South Plains Food Bank. The South Plains Food Bank serves residents of Floydada. The classes will hold contest throughout the drive. The South Plains Food Bank will run through December 6.

post_text: 5th graders began a unit on light. They did an in way to prove that light travels in a straight line. They used yarn and a flashlight to follow the path of light. Then they looked at what happens when light is reflected with a mirror. Ask your 5 th grader how light travels.

post_text: Mrs. Taylor’s 3rd grade Reading students had fun learning how to recognize Prefixes, Root Words, and Suffixes in class. Students had to “Scoot” around the room, from task card to task card. They read the card and separated the word by prefix/root word/suffix, then recorded it on their answer sheets.

Floydada "Spirit of the Winds" Marching Band - UIL Marching Contest 2019

Floydada High School Band
October 19, 2019 at 9:35 PM ·

The Floydada High School "Spirit of the Winds" Marching Band earned a division 2 rating at UIL Marching Contest today. UIL defines division 2 as a rating of "excellent," and we are all very happy for the bandmembers and proud of their efforts this marching season. For those of you who missed the performance, you can find the video here: https://youtu.be/MH7lZ62tEUc

post_text: Floydada ISD has applied to Collegiate Edu-Nation to become a Collegiate District. If accepted into this network, students will be able to earn enough college hours to earn at least an Associate's Degree and will have opportunities to earn other job-related skills and certificates. This will be at NO COST to students, thus saving parents thousands of dollars.

post_text: Physics students are learning about Newton’s laws of motion. They dropped a bowling ball and a basketball from the same height at the same time. The students made predictions before the drop of what they thought would happen. Afterwards, they discussed the results in class. Ask your Physics student why a bowling ball and a basketball will hit the ground at the same time when dropped from the same height at the same time.

post_text:
OCTOBER STUDENT AND STAFF OF THE MONTH

The Floydada I.S.D. Board met on Monday, October 7 and recognized the following students and staff for their efforts to make education the best it can be. Each month the staff selects students that exemplify education at its best and those students are recognized at the monthly school board meeting. The A.B.Duncan student recognized were Itzel Baltazar and Kanon Rainwater, grade 5. The Floydada Junior High Students of the month were Diana Carmona and O’Brian Diaz, grade 8. The Floydada High School students recognized were MaKayla Garcia and Tyson Snell, grade 12. The elementary support staff selected this month was Nelda Ochoa. The secondary support staff of the month was Dorcus Baker Congratulations to each of these students and employees and thank you for your hard work.

post_text:
September Student and Staff of the Month

The Floydada I.S.D. Board met on Tuesday, September 17 and recognized the following students and staff for their efforts to make education the best it can be. Each month the staff selects students that exemplify education at its best and those students are recognized at the monthly school board meeting. The A.B.Duncan student recognized were Kyra Segura and Brody Hughes, grade 6. The Floydada Junior High Students of the month were Giovanni Baltazar and Kylie Fipps, grade 8. The Floydada High School students recognized were Alexis Hernandez and Pablo Mendoza, grade 12. The elementary educator selected this month was Kristie Carroll, 4th & 5th Social Studies. The secondary employee of the month was Trey Rogge, English 2 & 3. Congratulations to each of these students and employees and thank you for your hard work.

post_text:
This school year will mark the fifteen year anniversary since Floydada ISD first participated in the Texas Technology Immersion Pilot program. This was the program that allowed Floydada Junior High to get Apple iBook G4 computers in 2004. And fun trivia fact, this is where the “TIP Room” got its name! The following year, FISD was forward thinking and expanded the program to the high school with local money. We were one of if not the first district in the area and state to do this at such a scale.

It’s all thanks our staff, administrators, technology staff, school board, students, and community that our program has continued this long and received national recognition. Thank you to everyone for being part of our 21st century learning!
text:
This school year will mark the fifteen year anniversary since Floydada ISD first participated in the Texas Technology Immersion Pilot program. This was the program that allowed Floydada Junior High to get Apple iBook G4 computers in 2004. And fun trivia fact, this is where the “TIP Room” got its name! The following year, FISD was forward thinking and expanded the program to the high school with local money. We were one of if not the first district in the area and state to do this at such a scale.

It’s all thanks our staff, administrators, technology staff, school board, students, and community that our program has continued this long and received national recognition. Thank you to everyone for being part of our 21st century learning!

post_text: Lubbock ISD will be hosting a College and Career Night and have invited surrounding schools to attend. The event will be held at the Texas Tech University United Spirit Arena from 5:30pm to 7:30pm on Monday, October 7, 2019. Approximately one hundred colleges, universities and technical institutes will be represented and the format will be “browse only.” Recruiters from the armed services will also be available to discuss educational opportunities available through military service. They will also be providing financial aid sessions that will be of benefit to parents and students.
